  <p>Bordeaux, the world's most prestigious wine region, produces exceptional wines that have set global standards for centuries. Understanding Bordeaux's diverse terroirs and wine styles is essential for any wine enthusiast seeking to explore France's most celebrated appellations.</p>

  <h2>Understanding Bordeaux Wine Regions</h2>
  
  <h3>Left Bank Bordeaux</h3>
  <p><strong>Appellations:</strong> Médoc, Haut-Médoc, Saint-Estèphe, Pauillac, Saint-Julien, Margaux</p>
  <p><strong>Primary Grape:</strong> Cabernet Sauvignon (60-70%)</p>
  <p><strong>Style:</strong> Structured, tannic, age-worthy wines with cassis and graphite notes</p>
  <p><strong>Food Pairing:</strong> Red meat, lamb, aged cheeses, rich stews</p>

  <h3>Right Bank Bordeaux</h3>
  <p><strong>Appellations:</strong> Saint-Émilion, Pomerol, Fronsac, Canon-Fronsac</p>
  <p><strong>Primary Grapes:</strong> Merlot (70-80%), Cabernet Franc</p>
  <p><strong>Style:</strong> Rounder, fruit-forward, more approachable with plum and chocolate notes</p>
  <p><strong>Food Pairing:</strong> Duck, pork, mushroom dishes, soft cheeses</p>

  <h2>Bordeaux Tasting Profiles</h2>
  
  <h3>Classic Bordeaux Characteristics</h3>
  
  <h4>Aroma Profile</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Primary:</strong> Blackcurrant, plum, cherry</li>
    <li><strong>Secondary:</strong> Violet, rose, herbs</li>
    <li><strong>Tertiary:</strong> Cedar, tobacco, leather, graphite</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>Structural Elements</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Acidity:</strong> Medium to medium-high</li>
    <li><strong>Tannins:</strong> Medium to high (varies by region)</li>
    <li><strong>Body:</strong> Medium to full-bodied</li>
    <li><strong>Alcohol:</strong> 12.5-14.5% ABV</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Bordeaux Food Pairing Guide</h2>
  
  <h3>Red Meat & Game</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Grilled ribeye steak</li>
    <li>Roasted leg of lamb</li>
    <li>Venison medallions</li>
    <li>Beef wellington</li>
    <li>Duck confit</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Rich Stews & Braises</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Coq au vin</li>
    <li>Beef bourguignon</li>
    <li>Osso buco</li>
    <li>Cassoulet</li>
    <li>Short rib braise</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Aged Cheeses</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Roquefort</li>
    <li>Aged Comté</li>
    <li>Stilton</li>
    <li>Camembert</li>
    <li>Aged Gouda</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Bordeaux Buying Guide</h2>
  
  <h3>Price Categories</h3>
  
  <h4>Entry Level ($15-30)</h4>
  <p>Bordeaux AOC and Bordeaux Supérieur wines offering classic regional character at accessible prices.</p>
  
  <h4>Premium ($50-150)</h4>
  <p>Cru Bourgeois and village-level wines from prestigious appellations with excellent aging potential.</p>
  
  <h4>Ultra-Premium ($200+)</h4>
  <p>Classified Growth châteaux and prestigious Right Bank estates offering legendary quality and investment potential.</p>

  <h3>Vintage Recommendations</h3>
  <p><strong>Exceptional Vintages:</strong> 2016, 2015, 2010, 2009, 2005 - Perfect for cellaring</p>
  <p><strong>Drinking Now:</strong> 2014, 2012, 2008, 2006 - Mature and ready to enjoy</p>
  <p><strong>Value Vintages:</strong> 2013, 2011 - Great quality at more accessible prices</p>

  <h2>Serving & Storage Tips</h2>
  
  <h3>Optimal Serving</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Temperature:</strong> 16-18°C (60-65°F)</li>
    <li><strong>Decanting:</strong> 1-2 hours for young wines, 30 minutes for mature</li>
    <li><strong>Glassware:</strong> Large Bordeaux bowl for optimal aeration</li>
    <li><strong>Opening:</strong> 30 minutes before serving minimum</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Aging Potential</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Classified Growths:</strong> 20-30+ years</li>
    <li><strong>Cru Bourgeois:</strong> 10-15 years</li>
    <li><strong>Bordeaux AOC:</strong> 5-10 years</li>
    <li><strong>Storage:</strong> 12-14°C, 70% humidity, dark</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h2>Expert Wine Recommendations</h2>
  
